<h2>Content Strategy and Publishing Workflows &#123;#ch5&#125;</h2>
<p>A headless CMS is only as good as the content flowing through it. The best architecture in the world will not rank without consistent, optimized publishing.</p>
<h3>Content Velocity for Headless Sites</h3>
<p>Google rewards consistent publishing combined with topical depth. Sites that rank publish at least 20 posts per month. Top performers publish 30 to 60.</p>
<p>The math is simple. Google needs content to crawl, index, and rank. Topical authority builds on volume plus quality plus interlinking. One post a month does not generate enough surface area for Google to understand what your site is about.</p>
<p>Headless CMS platforms make high-velocity publishing easier because content and presentation are separate. Your content team writes in the CMS. Your frontend handles display. Changes to design do not disrupt editorial workflows.</p>
<h3>Topic Clusters on Headless CMS</h3>
<p>The strongest content structure is the topic cluster. Pick a pillar topic. Write a 3,000+ word pillar post. Then write 10 to 20 cluster posts that go deep on subtopics and link back to the pillar.</p>
<p><strong>Example pillar:</strong> "Headless CMS for SEO" (this guide)</p>
<p><strong>Example clusters:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Sanity SEO best practices</li>
<li>Next.js headless CMS setup guide</li>
<li>Headless CMS vs WordPress for publishers</li>
<li>Contentful SEO configuration</li>
<li>Ghost vs headless WordPress comparison</li>
</ul>
<p>Each cluster post links to the pillar. The pillar links to every cluster post. Tag every post with the cluster identifier so your frontend can build related content modules automatically.</p>
<h3>API-Driven Publishing Workflows</h3>
<p>The real power of headless CMS for SEO is API-driven publishing. Content flows from creation tools through the CMS API to the frontend automatically.</p>
<p><strong>Workflow example:</strong></p>
